segments.text: In business, we were talking about the Corps of Cadets movement, the Goodrich incident.
How do you change the organization of the Corps?
And I did a little looking around.
In your history, you'll recall that the Corps at one time had a commandant of cadets who worked directly for the university.
And that's what I wanted.
I wanted somebody who was loyal to the institution and not to the Army or Navy or Air Force.

how do you do that henry how do you change the corps of cadets you know it's like moving a graveyard so what i did was create a committee in on which i asked the chief of staff of the marine corps chief of staff of the army the chief of navy education an admiral who's in charge of the naval pro naval education program
And the general who was in charge of our ROTC region to come and take a look at the Corps of Cadets.
And they were great.
Boy, they were great.
They came in and looked at it.
Have they ever done anything like this before?
Yes, they've done that before.
No, the Corps had not.
But these guys, and there was a woman, a general of the region, ROTC, they had done something like this before.
And the Admiral knew exactly what I was after.
And they were great.

They sat down with me when they first got here, and the general, the chief of the Marine Corps, whose name I will remember in a minute, who I really liked tremendously, he said, okay, let's start off with a key question.
What do you want out of this business?
And I said, well, I'll tell you exactly what I want, but it may not be what you think I ought to have.
That's what I wanted to know.
As long as you don't care if we don't give you exactly what you want.
I said, no, I'll tell you what I'd like, but you're here to tell me.
That's right.
If it's the wrong thing, tell me.
I told them I was hoping we'd get back to this.
They said, did you have this before?
Yes, at one time we had it, and we'd gotten away with it.
So they were here for three days.
They interviewed all kinds of corps members,
all the officers of the services who were stunned at all the stars sitting at that table.
And I knew I had to do this if I was going to change the Corps, Henry.
The board wasn't going to let me do a damn thing to it unless I went in with a blue ribbon report.
So I got a report saying this was indeed the thing to do, and what had happened in the Corps, the committee said, was reprehensible and should never be allowed to happen again.
Now, was this largely in response to the Goodrich incident?
Yes.
I think this was the Goodrich incident that triggered it.
There may have been one in between, but I think this was it.
And so I took this report to the board.
And what could the board say?
I mean, this thing was dripping with stars.
Every service was represented, including the ROTC reach.
Nobody on there lower than a general officer or an admiral.
So, man...
I had the board boxed.
The only time I ever did it.
So then I was able to, and I even, I asked him while I had him, after I saw the report, I said, who do you have that I ought to hire?
And there was some debate about this, and they finally said, look, there's a guy in the Air Force who's an Aggie.
He says, it's very important you get an Aggie who's about to retire, and he's a deputy
Commander Atlantic Fleet.
He's an Air Force officer.
His name is Tom Darley.
So I hired General Darley.
He had some good men under him, too, about that time.
Yeah.
Burton was the Army guy.
A good Marine officer, Colonel Johnson.
And there were two or three others, I can't remember.
But they were all so impressed with this committee that they were all walking around in attention.
Yeah.
Do you think that the Corps had pretty much dominated the character of Texas A&M?
Yes.
Before that time, during that time, still does?
I think it was trying still to dominate A&M during that time, but there was growing friction between it and the fraternities and sororities, as you know.
And it's now in such a minority status that I think it doesn't dominate it as it did, but it still presents
What I think is its great value, and I've always thought it was its great value, was that it is sort of the keeper of the keys of the tradition of the institution.
It is the thing that makes A&M different, and I think positively different, in the positive sense.
I think the Corps has always been a good influence, but it occasionally gets too wrapped up in itself, and then you get real problems.
That's when you have to do something like this.
Was Fred McClure one of the commanders, four commanders when you were here?
He was a black guy.
Was he corps commander or was he president of the student body?
President of the student body, that's right.
Was he a member of the corps?
Well, he had just gone before I got here.
He was wonderful.
I've always thought of the corps, one of his great assets and strengths, as a good minority group.
Absolutely.
Still is.
Still is.
What do you see as the future of the Corps at Texas A&M and military programs in general?
I can't see the Corps ever disappearing from Texas A&M.
I can't see.
I think that would be a disaster for the institution.
I know you and I share this same view.
What would you have at A&M?
You'd have another University of Texas, only a smaller one, a little bit.
You wouldn't have a distinctive institution.
with the kind of representation of tradition, which I think is vital to a place like this.
Do you think that is one of the unique qualities?
Oh, yes.
That's one of the reasons I wanted to come to A&M.
I really believed in the idea of the Corps doesn't have the motto of duty, honor, country, but it represents that.
And that, to me, is all to the good.
As an old tea sipper, it's been quite a revelation for me, too.
Yeah, isn't it?
It really is.
And I have come to be a great admirer of Coke, as you are.
Well, I don't want to... Oh, go on.
I'm having fun.
Oh, all right.
With the... We've talked about minority recruiting.
We've talked about the four cadets.
What about growth, just pure physical growth?
Was that a problem for you during your eight years?
Mm-hmm.
It was.
And Gordy and I, along with others, the deans all together, decided we were going to have to try to stop it.
Unbridled growth was going to lead to disaster because the budget was leveling off.
And it was hard for everybody to accept that, Henry, to stop growth.
It was hard for me to accept it.
It was secret.
It was hard for me to stop it because
I liked the thought that A&M was growing.
It made me feel that people loved the university and wanted to send their children here.
I liked that.
But at the same time, I knew we couldn't go on this way because we were going to lose quality with numbers.
The money was stopping so the library couldn't grow.
Scientific equipment couldn't keep up.
We weren't going to be able to keep up with classroom footage.
We were going to have to stop growth.
Now, how do you do that?
because the board has the same feeling I have.
It's very nice that wherever the board goes, people want to send their kids to A&M.
Was there any sense among, you always hear this gossip, among board members that they really did want A&M to be as big as Texas?
Oh, yeah.
Bigger.
Bigger.
Bigger.
Sure.
Sure.
So limiting would be very hard.
Mm-hmm.
Excuse me, there was no doubt that it was better already.
You understand that?
Oh, yeah, right.
But bigger, bigger was better.
So how do you persuade them that it ain't?
Well, the board had changed a little.
John Mobley had come on from Austin.
The guy from San Antonio, who runs all the radio stations,
Hayes?
Mayes.
Mayes was on.
There was a little more opening.
Who was the guy who later became chairman of the board?
I should remember his name well.
A very good friend of mine.
Ran the Granada.
Oh, sure.
Ellard, David Ellard.
David Ellard, sure.
You ever see him?
I see him every once in a while.
Talk to him often.
This group was more open to, the pitch I kept making and Gordy kept making to him, and the dean, was, look, we're not only trying to modernize A&M, we're trying to improve it.
to make it the best university in Texas and in the area.
Now that was something they could understand.
So we made a plan, an academic plan, to level off the growth.
And we had a long presentation to the board with all kinds of backup about why this had to be done.
You know, dollars versus people.
And they bought it.
They bought the idea of it.
Basically, what they did was slow growth through more selective recruiting.
That's right.
Selective recruiting.
They didn't like that because they loved to tell their constituents wherever they were, we'll take anybody.
Yeah, we'll take care of you.
But they bought the idea of slow growth and selective growth.
And we kept pointing out that the SAT numbers were going up.
We were getting better students, getting better students.
We were able to point out as the minority recruiting went along, we were not only getting more minorities, we were getting high-quality minorities, and we were keeping them.
We could recruit minorities, and we still have the best record in the state for keeping them once we get them, and the board liked that.
And the thing that really got them was the time we finally beat Rice and Texas in recruiting national merit scholars.
Beat them one year.
That was the greatest moment.
Oh, the board was so proud they went around popping their buttons.
What do you think was the most difficult time you had as president?
God, there were so many, Henry.
Was it athletics?
Athletics was the worst, I think.
Worst problem.
And minority recruiting was hard.
Minority recruiting was hard.
As I say, they did it, but it was tough.
What was the most difficult time you had or issue, let's say, with the board?
Was there any special?
There was one special day.
Totally surprised me.
I was not ready for this at all.
That's when you really get it.
That's when those things usually happen.
That's right.
I was summoned to the board.
I thought the board had left town.
I thought the board had left town, and I was summoned back.
I'd already headed for the golf course, so I come back in my golf club, and they're all sitting there looking at me.
The entree knew.
My biggest enemy on the board was Billy Mack McKenzie, who, for reasons I do not know to this day, never liked me from the day I got the job.
But he was always laying in the gap to get me, and he was sitting there literally enjoying this meeting, I could tell.
So I knew I was in big trouble.

and they were all looking at a copy of the battalion and there was some article i hadn't seen it and if i'd seen it it wouldn't have bothered me you know but there was an article in there critical of the board i don't know something they had they ought to have done maybe it had to do with minorities i don't know but anyway it was they were all pissed really and
So one of them, I don't remember who it was, said, we want you to fire the editor of the battalion by tonight and close the newspaper down.
Being totally unready for this, I didn't really know what to say, Henry.
And while I was reeling from the shock, someone else pitched in, and you will love this one.
Do you know that history professor who just said he is not in favor of mother home and country?
Yes.
I also knew, and don't put this in, that I had snuck him ten years.
By not using his full name but his initials, I'd gotten him tenure.
Oh, really?
That's right.
You were the only one who knows that.
But I'm proud of that.
And I said, yes, I know him.
Does that son of a bitch have tenure?
Yes, he does.
Well, fire him anyway.
And they meant it.
It was not a joke.
And I sat there looking a little stunned, I'm sure.
Maybe my mouth was open, I don't know.
And one of them said, if you won't do it, we'll get someone who will.
Is that clear enough for you?
So that put a new face on it.
And then John Cole spoke up.
And he said, well, Frank, isn't the issue of what the battalion says about us,
And isn't the issue of what this professor says about mother, home, and country protected under the rubric of academic freedom?
And I said, well, John, I would have thought so.
He said, well, gentlemen, we're on record as supporting academic freedom.
Can't we move on to something more fruitful?
And the whole thing collapsed like a busted balloon.
And defused it right there.
Right there.
You are greatly indebted to that man.
Don't tell me I have always known him.
That's a good story.
Isn't that a great story?
That's a great story.
Now there is a regent who was a regent.
Can't we move on to something more fruitful?
Well, I remember those times because that history professor was in my department.
I know he was.
I know he was.
And he gave me hell, too.
Well, you know, I still think we did the right thing.
Well, I know you did.
You did, too.
He was a great teacher.
Yeah.
He doesn't know how I snuck that tenure forward.
Also, there's something else you need to know.
You will find this not surprising, but I did when I first encountered him.
The board spent endless hours on building programming.
That was their main interest, building.
They had an edifice complex, literally.
But you send up a big pile of names for tenure, and they passed it in two minutes.
They never even read it.
And I thought, well, with people like the man you and I are talking about, they would have singled him out because they were so mad.
They didn't even read the list of tenure.
And this was the future of the university.
Yeah, maybe, you know, that's good.
Well, it had its good moments.
It had its good moments.
And one of the things that I put in that I'm proud of was a different way to review tenure and promotion.
You probably know that it changed.
It came up through the proper channels.
And before the final decision was made, I read every tenure recommendation.
And then, remember, I asked everybody to send up the ones they didn't want to promote.
Because I was afraid people were being deliberately ignored.
And I think that was the right thing to do.
I think a lot of structure and form development was not here before.
I think the old hierarchy had literally been bad.
That was it.
The deans and department heads.
My big failure, you want to know my big failure?
Yes.
I wanted to change it from heads to chairman.
Yeah.
And I never could make it.
Well, I guarantee you in history we did.
It was kind of over my dead body, I might add.
But it did.
Maybe not entirely, but certainly in practice.
Well, you know, I had suffered under a longstanding head.
Not suffered.
You know, I loved him.
But he'd been head of the department at Rice for 31 years.
Now, that is a bit long.
That is long.
We've had similar situations.
Yes, I know.
I know.
Yes, I know.
But then it seemed to me that we ought to, it didn't matter if you re-elected the same guy.
That'd be fine, but we ought to have a way to do that.
But I couldn't break that log jam.
Okay, let's close out, but with some kind of comment from you, if you don't mind, about where you see A&M going this next decade or thereafter.
I'm very worried.
I'm very worried that the legislature, in its wisdom, is going to do its end from the standpoint of money.
The expansion of the A&M system sounded good, but it's watering down a lot of the assets of the university.
I think that's true.
Now, Herb may have a different point of view, but it seems to me that

each of these new institutions feel that they ought to have some part of the pie of course which is why they want to get into the system and the puff was created to make texas and a m that was supposed to be the excellence fund and it's now in there you're operating off the available fund it's now the non-available fund one of my favorite stories going around would irritate the aggies at first and then they loved it is what is this two-thirds
This is one-third.
And that's the way that it was divided.
But we haven't got it anymore.
The available fund is down to zip, practically.
And it was, some years when I was in, it seems to me my memory has any kind of relevance still to reality.
At one point in one year, we had $60 million in the available fund.
which you could really do great things with.
If you had a good academic plan, you could really do great things.
So you think the financial constraints are there?
That's going to hurt us badly.
And every university does that.
Oh, yeah, yeah.
But it's going to be bad here because, and again, discounted because it may be me talking about the past, but I think we were really on a roll upward.
I think we were doing extremely well.
And I think it's plateauing because of money problems.
And that hurts you.
Sure.
Well, I think that's maybe a sand, but a good place to close.
Well, let me tell you one more thing.
I'm trying to remember what year this was.
This must have been about 86, when we were coming up to a new budget cycle.
And it was clear that we were going to go through the same mess in Austin that we'd had the previous budget cycle, 84.
And I knew we were going to, if we were lucky, very lucky, we might be even with the board, but we weren't going to have anything extra.
And what the legislature was doing consistently, and that's what's working so badly now, was driving us increasingly back on the AUF.
They'd say, you can give more money to the library, but take it out of the AUF.
And they'd give it to somebody else.
And at one point there, Gordy and I
and later Donald, were pumping a million dollars a year out of the available fund extra into the library.
You probably knew that because it was good for the history department.
Yeah, and it still wasn't enough.
It wasn't nearly enough, but that was our extra, you know.
So I had a meeting of all the, I had the vice president of the United States, Eddie Joe, and all the vice presidents and deans, no, the vice presidents and the,
and Gordy and them, and they were talking about the finances, and we had a big presentation on what the budget would look like and projecting it into the next year.

And they gave me three plans, like they always gave Lyndon, three plans, A, B, and C, and they always had it structured so you had to take C. They used to piss him off, you know, and this was really pissing me off, too.
C was the only one who was viable.
I said, look, there's a fourth one you haven't constructed yet.
I want you to construct me a budget for every college with 2% less than you have projected here on your program fee.
What?
I said, that's called the president's tax.
And we're going to tax every college 2% and put it in the kitty for next year.
And that's where the money came for the next year.
And it worked.
It worked.
You got it all back, but you got it back when you really need it.
I was very proud of that innovative system on the spur of the moment.
While you're on the subject, what do you think about future funding in terms of the talk about using the lottery money and all this kind of stuff?
I don't know what we're going to do.
I don't think university funding in Texas is ever going to be worth a tinker's damn until we get to state income tax.
I think that's what's going to have to happen, or some windfall profit from something.
But it looks to me, you know, the problem is that educational money, particularly higher education, is one earmarked fund that the legislature can get its hands on.
All the others are entitlements, and this they can grab.
And that's what's hurting us.
So you have to battle for it.
Oh, it's getting worse and worse.
I just feel for Eddie Joe and Bill and Herb when they go over to Austin.
I tell you, it is no fun.
How'd you happen to decide you were ready to leave the presidency?
Well, I got to, you know, I don't know if I can explain it except in schematic terms.
I got vibrations, feelings, that my time was about up.
I got the feeling that, you know, I could hang on a while, but I'd done about all I was going to be able to do.
And when you get the feeling that you're being tolerated
That's the time to get out before they push you out.
But you decided you wanted to stay at A&M.
Yeah, I liked A&M.
I didn't want to rush off somewhere else.
I had two or three places I might have gone, but I thought I'd stay here.
Because here I have a great opportunity to write books and enjoy myself and teach.
Yeah, I didn't want to leave A&M.
I liked it.
So you retired from the, or you stepped down from the presidency, affected when?
The end of the academic year 88.
And you became director of the Mosier Institute.
Yes, yes.
At that point.
Yeah, right.
And what was I going to tell you?
Oh, something I'd like to say in favor of the Board of Regents.
Every single

academic request academic request that the administration took to the board we got very good that's a very strong regard i think that's very important to be in the record all right sir thank you so much for your time you're welcome appreciate it very much and i may come back to you on the phone or the person and ask you would you explain this a little bit or something you're most welcome you're most welcome
But I think this would be a big help.
And as I say, it's going to be more of an impressionistic approach, I think, when I start writing.
Well, I'm glad you did it, because I never...
